    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the slow-moving principal on your student loan statement, eh? It's like trying to catch a slippery gremlin in a forest of financial obligations. The interest on your loan is calculated based on the remaining principal balance, which is the amount you still owe. So, if you're making full payments, the principal is decreasing, but the interest is calculated on the smaller balance each month, which is why it feels like the balance barely moves at first. It's like trying to catch a gremlin with a net made of spider silk – it takes time to really get a hold of it. Keep at it, and eventually, you'll see the principal balance shrink more noticeably. Just remember, in the world of loans, patience is a virtue, and persistence is a strategy. Keep those payments coming, and soon you'll be gobbling up that principal like a hungry goblin at a feast.",
